cus aureus","Escherichia coli"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeishmania\u003C/strong\u003E is a protozoan parasite that has developed mechanisms to evade the host\u0027s immune response. It can escape from the phagolysosome into the cytoplasm of the host cell, where it replicates. This ability allows it to avoid destruction by the host\u0027s immune system and contributes to its pathogenicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EBacillus anthracis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E has other mechanisms to evade the immune system, such as capsule formation, but does not escape into the cytoplasm\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E survives within the phagosome by preventing its fusion with the lysosome, but does not escape into the cytoplasm\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E produces toxins and other virulence factors but does not escape into the cytoplasm\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E has mechanisms to survive within host cells but does not typically escape into the cytoplasm to replicate\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Some pathogens have evolved mechanisms to evade the host\u0027s immune response by escaping from the phagolysosome into the cytoplasm.","Leishmania is an example of an organism that can avoid destruction by escaping into the cytoplasm and replicating within the phagocyte."],"references":["Steverding D. The history of leishmaniasis. Parasit Vectors. 2017 Feb 15;10(1):82. doi: 10.1186/s13071-017-2028-5. PMID: 28202044; PMCID: PMC5312593.","Sastry, A. S., \u0026 Bhat, S. (2018). Essentials of medical micro